{{For|the doctor|John Farmery (physician)}}
'''John Farmery''' (1591<U+2013>1647) was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]]  in 1640. He supported the [[Cavaliers|Royalist]] side in the [[English Civil War]].

Farmery was the son of William Farmery, Rector of Heapham, Lincolnshire and his wife Cassandra Newland of Hackney.<ref name=Springthorpe>[http://www.springthorpe-village.org.uk/history/history3.html Lincolnshire Village, Springthorpe]</ref> He was baptised at Springthorpe, Lincolnshire on 24 February 1591. He matriculated from [[St John's College, Cambridge]] at Easter 1607. He was awarded BA in 1611 and MA in 1614 and LLD in 1620.<ref>{{acad|id= FRMY607J2|name=Farmery, John}}</ref> In 1624, he was incorporated at [[Oxford University]]. He was admitted as an advocate on 6 May 1637 and was chancellor of the diocese of Lincoln. 

In April 1640, Farmery was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lincoln (UK Parliament constituency)|Lincoln]] in the [[Short Parliament]].<ref name=Willis>{{Cite Notitia Parliamentaria|converted=1|part=2|pages=229<U+2013>239}}</ref> He received regimental command in the Royalist army in the civil war.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=3dbnAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=%22John+Farmery%22+chancellor&source=bl&ots=j-JFWPYYcr&sig=v3iMrthtJ8uYivSIhEMxQp7gWQA&hl=en&ei=DyRcTf7tM8WwhQfCldmcDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CDIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Farmery%22%20chancellor&f=false P. R. Newman ''The old service: Royalist regimental colonels and the Civil War, 1642-46'']</ref>
 
Farmery died at the age of 56.

Farmery married and left a son also named John.<ref name=Springthorpe/>

